url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-03-14-life-is-strange-episode-2-release-date|title=Life is Strange: Episode 2 release date revealed|first=Tom|last=Phillips|date=14 March 2015|work=[[Eurogamer]]|accessdate=14 March 2015|archivedate=15 March 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315053810/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-03-14-life-is-strange-episode-2-release-date|url-status=live}}</ref>|'''Episode 3'''|19 May 2015<ref name=\"19 May 2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/05/13/life-is-strange-episode-3-chaos-theory-gets-a-release-date |title=Life is Strange: Episode 3 \u2013 Chaos Theory Gets a Release Date |first=Luke |last=Karmali |date=13 May 2015 |work=[[IGN]] |accessdate=13 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150516041004/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/05/13/life-is-strange-episode-3-chaos-theory-gets-a-release-date |archivedate=16 May 2015  }}</ref>|'''Episode 4'''|28 July 2015<ref name=\"28 July 2015\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2015/07/23/life-is-strange-episode-4-release-date-announced-as-sales-hit-one-million-copies/ |title=Life is Strange episode 4 release date announced as sales hit one million copies |first=Shabana |last=Arif |date=23 July 2015 |work=[[VG247]] |accessdate=23 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723224952/http://www.vg247.com/2015/07/23/life-is-strange-episode-4-release-date-announced-as-sales-hit-one-million-copies/ |archivedate=23 July 2015  }}</ref>|'''Episode 5'''|20 October 2015}}\n| genre       = [[Graphic adventure game|Graphic adventure]]\n| modes       = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n| director    = {{Unbulleted list|Raoul Barbet|Michel Koch}}\n| producer    = Luc Baghadoust\n| designer    = {{Unbulleted list|Baptiste Moisan|Sebastien Judit|Sebastien Gaillard}}<!-- LEAD DESIGNERS ONLY -->\n| artist      = {{Unbulleted list| Michel Koch|Kenny Laurent|Amaury Balandier}}<!-- ART DIRECTOR AND LEAD ARTISTS ONLY -->\n| writer      = {{Unbulleted list|Christian Divine|Jean-Luc Cano}}\n| composer    = [[Jonathan Morali]]\n| series      = <!--Wikidata-->\n}}\n\n'''''Life Is Strange''''' is an episodic [[graphic adventure]] video game developed by [[Dontnod Entertainment]] and published by [[Square Enix]] for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox 360]], [[Xbox One]], [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]]. The game was released in five episodes periodically throughout 2015. The game's plot focuses on Max Caulfield, an 18-year-old photography student who discovers that she has the ability to [[Time travel|rewind time]] at any moment, leading her every choice to enact the [[butterfly effect]]. After having foreseen an approaching storm, Max must take on the responsibility to prevent it from destroying her town. The player's actions will adjust the narrative as it unfolds, and reshape it once allowed to travel back in time. [[Quest (video gaming)#Gather quests|Fetch quests]] and making environmental changes represent the forms of [[Puzzle video game|puzzle solving]] in addition to using [[Dialog tree|branching choices]] for conversation.\n\nDevelopment of ''Life Is Strange'' began in April 2013. It was formed with an episodic format in mind, for reasons both financial and creative. The developers conducted field research on the setting by travelling to the [[Pacific Northwest]], and subverted known [[archetype]]s to make the characters. Player feedback influenced the adjustments made to the episodes. Story and [[character arc]] serve as the central point in the game. During its release, ''Life Is Strange'' received generally favourable reviews commending the character development, rewind game mechanic and tackling of [[taboo]] subjects. Common criticisms included the [[slang]] that was used, poor [[Lip sync|lip-syncing]] in earlier episodes, and [[Tone (literature)|tonal]] inconsistencies in the story. It received over 75 Game of the Year awards and listings. It has sold over three million copies as of May 2017. A prequel, ''[[Life Is Strange: Before the Storm]]'', was released in August 2017, and a sequel, ''[[Life Is Strange 2]]'', in September 2018.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[Image:Life Is Strange Gameplay.png|thumb|left|250px|Players are able to rewind an event within a certain interval of time.|alt=The player character uses the time travel game mechanic. The timer display is visible on-screen.]]\n''Life Is Strange'' is a [[Graphic adventure game|graphic adventure]] played from a [[Virtual camera system#Third-person view|third-person view]].<ref name=\"rendering\" /> The mechanic of rewinding time allows the player to redo almost any action that has been taken.<ref name=\"repercussion\" /><ref name=\"checkpoint\">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/1/9/7522567/life-is-strange-release |title=It's time to pay attention to Life is Strange |first=Colin |last=Campbell |date=9 January 2015 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=21 July 2015 |archivedate=10 January 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110023923/http://www.polygon.com/2015/1/9/7522567/life-is-strange-release |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The player can examine and interact with objects, which enables [[Puzzle video game|puzzle solving]] in the form of [[Quest (video gaming)#Gather quests|fetch quests]] and making changes to the environment.<ref name=\"rendering\" /><ref name=\"interfere\" /> Items that are collected before time travelling will be kept in the inventory after the fact.<ref name=\"inventory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/gaming/news/a623826/life-is-strange-developer-diary-explores-rewind-feature.html#~p2f4kmNfcbwQbB|title=Life Is Strange developer diary explores rewind feature|first=Liam|last=Martin|date=23 January 2015|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=24 January 2015|archivedate=28 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128133135/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/gaming/news/a623826/life-is-strange-developer-diary-explores-rewind-feature.html#~p77mxhIJlKUNKi|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe player can explore various locations in the fictional setting of Arcadia Bay and communicate with [[non-player character|non-playable characters]].<ref name=\"NPC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/xboxone/life-is-strange-episode-2--out-of-time |title=Life is Strange: Episode 2 \u2013 Out of Time Review |first=Peter |last=Paras |date=31 March 2015 |work=[[Game Revolution]] |accessdate=11 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208050012/http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/xboxone/life-is-strange-episode-2--out-of-time |archivedate=8 December 2015  }}</ref><ref name=\"communicate\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/05/19/life-is-strange-episode-3-review |title=Life Is Strange \u2013 Episode 3 Review |first=Mitch |last=Dyer |date=19 May 2015 |work=[[IGN]] |accessdate=11 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029063709/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/05/19/life-is-strange-episode-3-review |archivedate=29 October 2015  }}</ref> Dialogue exchanges can be rewound while [[Dialog tree|branching options]] are used for conversation.<ref name=\"tree1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/life-is-strange-is-a-world-you-ll-want-to-lose-yourself-in-279555.phtml|title=Life is Strange is a world you'll want to lose yourself in|first=Brett|last=Makedonski|date=13 August 2014|work=[[Destructoid]]|accessdate=11 November 2014|archivedate=12 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112041142/http://www.destructoid.com/life-is-strange-is-a-world-you-ll-want-to-lose-yourself-in-279555.phtml|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"tree2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/86683/life-is-strange-impressions-stranger-by-the-minute|title=Life is Strange impressions: Stranger by the minute|first=Steven|last=Wong|date=14 October 2014|work=[[Shacknews]]|accessdate=21 July 2015|archivedate=16 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016063410/http://www.shacknews.com/article/86683/life-is-strange-impressions-stranger-by-the-minute|url-status=live}}</ref> Once an event is reset, the details provided earlier are permitted to avail themselves in the future.<ref name=\"reset\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/life_is_strange/b/pc/archive/2015/01/23/dontnod-details-the-rules-of-time-manipulation-in-life-is-strange.aspx|title=Life Is Strange Has Strict Time Travel Rules And A Unique Photography Aesthetic|first=Mike|last=Futter|date=23 January 2015|work=[[Game Informer]]|accessdate=24 January 2015|archivedate=27 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150127152137/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/life_is_strange/b/pc/archive/2015/01/23/dontnod-details-the-rules-of-time-manipulation-in-life-is-strange.aspx|url-status=live}}</ref> In some instances, choices in dialogue will alter and affect the story through short or long-term consequences.<ref name=\"shortlong\">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/10/10/6954961/life-is-strange-story-choices-matter-dontnod|title=Do your choices matter if you can just rewind time and redo them?|first=Samit|last=Sarkar|date=10 October 2014|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=12 November 2014|archivedate=12 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112030805/http://www.polygon.com/2014/10/10/6954961/life-is-strange-story-choices-matter-dontnod|url-status=live}}</ref> For each one of the choices, something good in the short-term could turn out worse later.<ref name=\"repercussion\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-09-10-life-is-strange-it-takes-time-to-be-different|title=Life is Strange: It takes time to be different|first=Robert|last=Purchese|date=12 September 2014|work=[[Eurogamer]]|accessdate=11 November 2014|archivedate=6 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206232913/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-09-10-life-is-strange-it-takes-time-to-be-different|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n''Life Is Strange'' is set in the fictional town of Arcadia Bay, [[Oregon]], and is told from the perspective of Maxine \"Max\" Caulfield (Hannah Telle), a twelfth-grade student attending Blackwell Academy during October 2013. During photography class with her teacher Mark Jefferson ([[Derek Phillips (actor)|Derek Phillips]]), Max experiences a vision of a lighthouse being destroyed by a swelling [[tornado]]. Leaving for the restroom to regain her composure, she witnesses classmate Nathan Prescott (Nik Shriner) kill a girl in a fit of rage. In a single, sudden effort, she develops the ability to [[Time travel|rewind time]] and rescues the girl, revealed to be her childhood friend [[Chloe Price]] ([[Ashly Burch]]). The two reunite and go for a walk at the lighthouse, where Max reveals to Chloe her capacity to travel back in time. It is established that the vision is rather the reckoning of a future event: a storm approaching the town.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Life Is Strange|developer=Dontnod Entertainment|publisher=Square Enix|date=30 January 2015|platform=Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 4, PlayStation 3, Xbox One, Xbox 360|level=Chrysalis}}</ref> The next day, Max observes fellow student Kate Marsh (Dayeanne Hutton) being bullied for a [[viral video]] depicting her kissing several students at a party.<ref name=\"chrysal15\">{{cite video game|title=Life Is Strange|developer=Dontnod Entertainment|publisher=Square Enix|date=24 March 2015|platform=Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 4, PlayStation 3, Xbox One, Xbox 360|level=Out of Time}}</ref>\n\nWhen Max meets Chloe at the diner where her mother Joyce ([[Cissy Jones]]) works, they decide to experiment with Max's power at Chloe's secret scrapyard hideout. However, strain causes Max to have a nosebleed and faint. Chloe takes her back to Blackwell, but class is halted when everyone is called out to the courtyard. Kate commits suicide by jumping off the roof of the girls' dorm. Max manages to rewind and time stops unexpectedly as she reaches Kate, giving Max the opportunity to convince her to come down. Max ultimately resolves to uncover what happened to Kate and Chloe's missing friend Rachel Amber.<ref name=\"chrysal15\" /> Max and Chloe break into the principal's office that night to investigate and enter the pool for a swim before evading David Madsen (Don McManus), head of security at Blackwell and Chloe's stepfather, and fleeing back to Chloe's place. The next morning, they sneak into the [[motorhome]] of Frank Bowers (Daniel Bonjour), drug dealer and friend of Rachel, and learn that Rachel was in a relationship with Frank and lied to Chloe about it, causing Chloe to storm off feeling betrayed. Max returns to her dormitory and examines a childhood photo of her and Chloe, but is suddenly transported to the day the picture was taken. Max prevents Chloe's father William ([[Joe Ochman]]) from dying in a traffic collision, which inadvertently creates an [[Multiverse|alternative reality]] where William is alive but Chloe has been [[Paralysis|paralysed from the neck down]] as a result of a collision in her own car.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Life Is Strange|developer=Dontnod Entertainment|publisher=Square Enix|date=19 May 2015|platform=Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 4, PlayStation 3, Xbox One, Xbox 360|level=Chaos Theory}}</ref>\n\nMax uses the photo to undo her decision and return to the present day, restoring Chloe's health. Continuing their investigation, Max and Chloe obtain clues leading them to an abandoned barn owned by the influential Prescott family. They discover a hidden bunker containing pictures of Kate and Rachel tied up and intoxicated, with Rachel being buried at Chloe's secret hideout. They hurry back to the scrapyard and find Rachel's grave, much to Chloe's despair. Max follows Chloe at the school party to confront Nathan, believing he will target fellow student Victoria Chase (Dani Knights). They receive a text from Nathan threatening to destroy the evidence, returning them to the scrapyard. All of a sudden, the two are ambushed by Jefferson, who [[Anesthesia|anaesthetises]] Max and kills Chloe with a shot to the head. Max is kidnapped and held captive in the \"[[Darkroom|Dark Room]]\", a place Jefferson has been drugging and photographing young girls to capture their innocence. Jefferson also reveals that he took Nathan on as a personal student, but killed him before abducting Max due to him giving Rachel an overdose when he tried to mimic Jefferson's work, and intends to do the same to Max after he has the photos he wants.  Max escapes into a photograph and emerges back at the beginning in Jefferson's class. She alerts David, getting Jefferson (and Nathan) arrested.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Life Is Strange|developer=Dontnod Entertainment|publisher=Square Enix|date=28 July 2015|platform=Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 4, PlayStation 3, Xbox One, Xbox 360|level=Dark Room}}</ref>\n\nMax is given the opportunity to go to [[San Francisco]] and have one of her photos displayed in an art gallery. She calls Chloe from the event, realising that, for all her effort, the storm has reached Arcadia Bay. Max travels back to the time at which she took the gallery photo, which eventually leads her to sojourn alternative realities as they devolve into a [[dream]]scape nightmare. Max and Chloe finally return to the lighthouse and confront the fact that Max brought the storm into existence by saving Chloe from being shot by Nathan earlier in the week. The only way to prevent it is for Max to go back to that moment via a photo she took and allow Chloe to be killed by Nathan. Max must make a choice: sacrifice Chloe's life to save Arcadia Bay, or sacrifice Arcadia Bay to spare Chloe.<ref name=\"Life Is Strange\">{{cite video game|title=Life Is Strange|developer=Dontnod Entertainment|publisher=Square Enix|date=20 October 2015|platform=Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 4, PlayStation 3, Xbox One, Xbox 360|level=Polarized}}</ref>\n<!-- Do not add the aftermath of the choices here. This section only details what HAS to happen.  -->\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Raoul Barbet & Michel Koch on Life Is Strange.webm|thumb|right|alt=Gameplay video|250px|Barbet and Koch describe the game and discuss the role of protagonist Max Caulfield.]]\n''Life Is Strange'' was [[Dontnod Entertainment]]'s second title with a female protagonist. Dontnod published a developer diary that said most prospective publishers were unwilling to publish a game unless it had a male protagonist.<ref name=\"square1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/other-publishers-told-us-to-make-it-a-male-lead-ch/1100-6424577/ |title=\"Other Publishers Told Us to Make It a Male Lead Character,\" Life is Strange Dev Says |first=Emanuel |last=Maiberg |date=10 January 2015 |work=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=21 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719152644/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/other-publishers-told-us-to-make-it-a-male-lead-ch/1100-6424577/ |archivedate=19 July 2015  }}</ref><ref name=\"square2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/139401-Publishers-Disliked-Dontnods-Life-is-Strange-Having-Female-Leads|title=Publishers Wanted Life is Strange Devs to Make Leads Male|first=Sarah|last=LeBoeuf|date=11 January 2015|work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]|accessdate=12 January 2015|archivedate=6 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206164909/http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/139401-Publishers-Disliked-Dontnods-Life-is-Strange-Having-Female-Leads|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Most publishers had the same objection to Dontnod's first project, ''[[Remember Me (video game)|Remember Me]]''.<ref name=\"first\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/publishers-said-you-cant-have-a-female-character-says-remember-me-dev/1100-6405550/|title=Publishers said 'You can't have a female character,' says Remember Me dev|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|date=19 March 2013|work=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=12 November 2014|archivedate=29 December 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131229210302/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/publishers-said-you-cant-have-a-female-character-says-remember-me-dev/1100-6405550/|url-status=live}}</ref> Dontnod CEO Oskar Guilbert also challenged the idea at the start.<ref name=\"3dg3\">{{cite magazine|title=Edge #293|first=Ben|last=Barnes|magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]|location=p. 94-97|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=June 2016}}</ref> [[Square Enix]] was the only publisher with no intention to change the female protagonist.<ref name=\"hip to be square\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/publishers-wanted-to-change-life-is-stranges-protagonis-1678811522 |title=Publishers Wanted To Change Life Is Strange's Protagonists Into Men |first=Mike |last=Rougeau |date=11 January 2015 |work=[[Kotaku]] |accessdate=31 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117104746/http://kotaku.com/publishers-wanted-to-change-life-is-stranges-protagonis-1678811522 |archivedate=17 November 2015  }}</ref>\n\nDevelopment of ''Life Is Strange'' began in April 2013 with a team of 15, and more people were added when the collaboration with Square Enix began.<ref name=\"development\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/videos/life-is-strange-developer-diary-a-new-beginning/2300-6422919/ |title=Life is Strange \u2013 Developer Diary: A New Beginning |first=Gajan |last=Kulasingham |date=9 January 2015 |work=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=21 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209052241/http://www.gamespot.com/videos/life-is-strange-developer-diary-a-new-beginning/2300-6422919/ |archivedate=9 February 2015  }}</ref><ref name=\"team\">{{cite web|url=http://www.momenta.online/2016/02/edouard-caplain-on-the-art-behind-life-is-strange/|title=Edouard Caplain on the Art Behind Life Is Strange|date=9 February 2016|work=Momenta|accessdate=18 February 2016|archivedate=27 July 2016|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160727023538/http://www.momenta.online/2016/02/edouard-caplain-on-the-art-behind-life-is-strange/|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Dontnod told Square Enix about ''Life Is Strange'' only after Square Enix turned down a [[Sales presentation|pitch]] for a larger game.<ref name=\"solicited success\" /><ref name=\"pitch on\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/they-originally-pitched-a-different-game-how-square-enix-discovered-life-is-strange/0153982 |title='They originally pitched a different game': how Square Enix discovered Life Is Strange |first=Christopher |last=Dring |date=7 August 2015 |work=[[MCV (magazine)|MCV]] |accessdate=31 March 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506210100/http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/they-originally-pitched-a-different-game-how-square-enix-discovered-life-is-strange/0153982 |archivedate=6 May 2016  }}</ref> Before signing with Square Enix, ''Life Is Strange'' was imagined as a full-length video game that Dontnod would self-publish. However, the publisher surmised that it would be more successful as an episodic title.<ref name=\"3dg3\" /> The game was originally codenamed ''What If'' but then retitled to distinguish itself from the [[The F Word (2013 film)|film of the same name]].<ref name=\"what if\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/square-enix-s-life-is-strange-considered-100-diffe/1100-6425742/ |title=Square Enix's Life is Strange Considered 100 Different Names |first=Eddie |last=Makuch |date=6 March 2015 |work=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=7 March 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150307215843/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/square-enix-s-life-is-strange-considered-100-diffe/1100-6425742/ |archivedate=7 March 2015  }}</ref>\n\n''Life Is Strange'' was born from the rewind mechanic idea, which the developer had already experimented on with their last game ''Remember Me''. The lead character Max was created with the ability to rewind time to supplement this mechanism.<ref name=\"birth\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/5/19/8612335/life-is-strange-making-of |title=How adventure game Life is Strange blends time travel and teen drama |first=Andrew |last=Webster |date=19 May 2015 |work=[[The Verge]] |accessdate=19 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150520104539/http://www.theverge.com/2015/5/19/8612335/life-is-strange-making-of |archivedate=20 May 2015  }}</ref> The episodic format was decided upon by the studio for creative reasons, financial restrictions<ref name=\"format\">{{cite web|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/life-is-stranges-triforce-of-influences|title=Life is Strange's \"Triforce\" of Influences|first=Kat|last=Bailey|date=31 January 2015|work=[[Eurogamer#Subsidiaries|USgamer]]|accessdate=1 February 2015|archivedate=2 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202123538/http://www.usgamer.net/articles/life-is-stranges-triforce-of-influences|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[marketing]] purposes,<ref name=\"aggregated\" /> allowing them to tell the story in its preferred slow pace.<ref name=\"slow pace\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/apr/26/life-is-strange-episodic-video-game-dontnod |title=Life Is Strange: episodic video games prove as addictive as episodic TV |first=Calum |last=Marsh |date=26 April 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=26 April 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518090434/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/apr/26/life-is-strange-episodic-video-game-dontnod |archivedate=18 May 2015  }}</ref> The [[Pacific Northwest]] was picked as the setting for the purpose of conveying a [[Nostalgia|nostalgic]] and autumnal feel to the game.<ref name=\"setting\">{{cite web|url=http://gamerhub.tv/videos/life-is-strange-gameplay-preview-interview/2014/08/27/|title=Life Is Strange Gameplay Preview Interview|date=27 August 2014|work=GamerHub|accessdate=11 November 2014|archivedate=12 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112032016/http://gamerhub.tv/videos/life-is-strange-gameplay-preview-interview/2014/08/27/|url-status=live}}</ref> The development team visited the region,<ref name=\"shortlong\" /> took photographs, looked at local newspapers and used [[Google Street View]] to make sure the environment was accurately portrayed.<ref name=\"archetypes\" /><ref name=\"googlestreetview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2015/01/29/life-is-strange-pc-ps4-xbox-one-video/|title=Final Life is Strange developer diary focuses on music, voice actors|first=Stephany|last=Nunneley|date=29 January 2015|work=[[VG247]]|accessdate=29 January 2015|archivedate=29 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150129233119/http://www.vg247.com/2015/01/29/life-is-strange-pc-ps4-xbox-one-video/|url-status=live}}</ref> It was decided early on that most of the budget be spent on the writing and voice actors.<ref name=\"release schedule 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-03-18-publishers-wanted-life-is-stranges-main-character-to-be-a-guy-qtes-added|title=Life is Strange dev talks lip-syncing, release schedule and publisher demands|first=Tom|last=Phillips|date=18 March 2015|work=[[Eurogamer]]|accessdate=18 March 2015|archivedate=18 March 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318133732/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-03-18-publishers-wanted-life-is-stranges-main-character-to-be-a-guy-qtes-added|url-status=live}}</ref> The original story was written in French by Jean-Luc Cano, and converted into a game script by the co-directors and design team. It was subsequently handed over to Christian Divine and Cano to be fine tuned in English.<ref name=\"script process\">{{cite web|url=http://www.redbull.com/en/games/stories/1331743857254/life-is-strange-interview |title=Be kind, rewind: The making of Life Is Strange |first=Damien |last=McFerran |date=28 August 2015 |work=[[Red Bull|Red Bull Games]] |accessdate=30 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150831002923/http://www.redbull.com/en/games/stories/1331743857254/life-is-strange-interview |archivedate=31 August 2015  }}</ref><ref name=\"cano\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-04-09-life-is-strange |title=Life is Strange team talk fan theories, that season finale and more |first=Tom |last=Phillips |date=18 April 2016 |work=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=20 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420131057/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-04-09-life-is-strange |archivedate=20 April 2016  }}</ref> Story and [[Character arc|character development]] were highlighted over [[Graphic adventure game#Point-and-click adventure|point-and-click]] puzzles,<ref name=\"highlighting\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2015/01/13/life-is-strange-is-for-telltale_heavy-rain-fans/|title=Life is Strange: \"this is definitely a game for the Telltale and Heavy Rain fans\"|first=Brenna|last=Hillier|date=13 January 2015|work=[[VG247]]|accessdate=20 July 2015|archivedate=13 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113184014/http://www.vg247.com/2015/01/13/life-is-strange-is-for-telltale_heavy-rain-fans/|url-status=live}}</ref> making choice and consequence integral to how the narrative unfolds.<ref name=\"choice\">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/8/11/5990851/life-is-strange-dontnod-entertainment-ps4-ps3-xbox-one-360-pc|title=Life is Strange, episodic adventure game, coming from Remember Me dev|first=Samit|last=Sarkar|date=11 August 2014|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=11 November 2014|archivedate=6 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206232452/http://www.polygon.com/2014/8/11/5990851/life-is-strange-dontnod-entertainment-ps4-ps3-xbox-one-360-pc|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannah Telle auditioned for Max Caulfield in July 2014 and was offered the part; [[Ashly Burch]] auditioned for both Max and her given role Chloe Price. The recording sessions were done in [[Los Angeles]], California, with the French developer brought in via [[Skype]].<ref name=\"audition 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/09/12/hannah-telle-involvement-in-life-is-strange-is-the-greatest-honor-2/166374/ |title=Hannah Telle: Involvement in Life Is Strange is the 'Greatest Honor' |first=Adnan |last=Riaz |date=12 September 2015 |work=Hardcore Gamer |accessdate=22 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119063952/http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/09/12/hannah-telle-involvement-in-life-is-strange-is-the-greatest-honor-2/166374/ |archivedate=19 November 2015  }}</ref><ref name=\"audition 2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/videos/life-is-strange-episodic-heartstrings-kinda-funny-/2300-6425679/ |title=Life Is Strange: Episodic Heartstrings \u2013 Kinda Funny at E3 2015 |first=Jeremy |last=Jayne |date=18 June 2015 |work=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=22 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151103172236/http://www.gamespot.com/videos/life-is-strange-episodic-heartstrings-kinda-funny-/2300-6425679/ |archivedate=3 November 2015  }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Life Is Strange.gif|thumb|left|Key art for episode five from rough concept to final version.]]\n\nAlthough it holds significant differences from ''Remember Me'', the game addresses similar themes of [[memory]] and [[Identity (philosophy)|identity]].<ref name=\"memoryidentity\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2014/08/13/gamescom-2014-how-life-is-strange-gets-female-protagonists-right|title=Gamescom 2014: How 'Life is Strange' Gets Female Protagonists Right|first=Brian|last=Albert|date=13 August 2014|work=[[IGN]]|accessdate=11 November 2014|archivedate=12 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112052448/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/08/13/gamescom-2014-how-life-is-strange-gets-female-protagonists-right|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Life Is Strange'' was specified as an [[Analog device|analogue]] look at human identity in contrast to ''Remember Me'', the [[Digital media|digital]] view of the same theme.<ref name=\"analogue\">{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-feature/2015/01/28/feature-life-is-strange-interview-and-hands-on-impressions|title=FEATURE: \"Life is Strange\" Interview and Hands-on Impressions|first=Nate|last=Ming|date=29 January 2015|work=[[Crunchyroll]]|accessdate=29 January 2015|archivedate=29 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150129193102/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-feature/2015/01/28/feature-life-is-strange-interview-and-hands-on-impressions|url-status=live}}</ref> Running on an improved version of [[Unreal Engine#Unreal Engine 3|Unreal Engine 3]], it makes use of the tools and special effects like [[High-dynamic-range rendering|lighting]] and [[depth of field]] engineered for ''Remember Me'' as well as subsequent advances.<ref name=\"characters\">{{cite web|url=http://thegamefanatics.com/2014/10/12/life-strange-brief-yet-delightful-look-next-game-behind-developers-remember|title=Life is Strange A Brief yet Delightful Look at the Next Game Behind the Developers of Remember Me|first=Carlos|last=Ovalle|date=12 October 2014|work=The Game Fanatics|accessdate=12 November 2014|archivedate=12 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112072937/http://thegamefanatics.com/2014/10/12/life-strange-brief-yet-delightful-look-next-game-behind-developers-remember|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"format\" /> Visual effects like [[Image editing|post-processes]], [[Multiple exposure|double exposure]] and overlapping [[particle system|screen space particles]] were used as an artistic approach to be displayed while the lead character rewinds time.<ref name=\"obstacles\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/watch-life-is-strange-dev-talks-time-travel-butter/1100-6424849/ |title=Watch: Life is Strange Dev Talks Time-Travel Butterfly Effect in New Video |first=Eddie |last=Makuch |date=23 January 2015 |work=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=24 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150125111127/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/watch-life-is-strange-dev-talks-time-travel-butter/1100-6424849/ |archivedate=25 January 2015  }}</ref> The textures seen in the game were entirely hand painted, adapted to achieve what art director Michel Koch called \"impressionistic rendering\".<ref name=\"rendering\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamereactor.eu/previews/249994/Life+is+Strange/ |title=One of the oddest reveals of Gamescom also proved to be one of the most interesting. Here's what the Remember Me developers did next. |first=Christian |last=Gaca |date=22 August 2014 |work=[[Gamereactor]] |accessdate=11 November 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221190043/http://www.gamereactor.eu/previews/249994/Life%2Bis%2BStrange/ |archivedate=21 December 2014  }}</ref> Elements were adjusted based on player feedback,<ref name=\"birth\" /> with influences like ''[[The Walking Dead (video game)|The Walking Dead]]'', ''[[Gone Home]]''{{efn|Dontnod started working on the game before ''Gone Home'' was released.<ref name=\"note2\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/animationscoop/video-game-spotlight-life-is-strange-20141223|title=VIDEO GAME SPOTLIGHT: \"Life Is Strange\"|first=Cydney|last=Fisher|date=23 December 2014|work=[[Indiewire]]|accessdate=29 January 2015|archivedate=27 December 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227162853/http://blogs.indiewire.com/animationscoop/video-game-spotlight-life-is-strange-20141223|url-status=live}}</ref>}} and ''[[Heavy Rain]]'' in mind.<ref name=\"analogue\" /><ref name=\"influences\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/manifesto/juno--donnie-darko--gone-home--life-is-strange-30843#/slide/8|title=Juno + Donnie Darko + Gone Home = Life is Strange|first=Blake|last=Peterson|date=26 January 2015|work=[[Game Revolution]]|accessdate=29 January 2015|archivedate=29 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150129222908/http://www.gamerevolution.com/manifesto/juno--donnie-darko--gone-home--life-is-strange-30843#/slide/8|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Additional sources of inspiration include the [[visual novel]] ''[[Danganronpa]]'', in terms of balancing gameplay and story,<ref name=\"catcher\"/> and the [[novel]]  ''[[The Catcher in the Rye]]'', whose protagonist [[Holden Caulfield]] shares a surname with Max, the game's lead.<ref name=\"catcher\">{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2015/02/05/life-strange-director-talks-theme-identity-visual-novels/|title=Life Is Strange Director Talks About The Theme Of \"Identity\" And Visual Novels|date=5 February 2015|work=Siliconera|accessdate=6 February 2015|archivedate=10 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210122205/http://www.siliconera.com/2015/02/05/life-strange-director-talks-theme-identity-visual-novels/|url-status=live}}</ref> The characters were created using known [[archetype]]s, at first to establish an entry point for the player, and then to subvert them.<ref name=\"archetypes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.idigitaltimes.com/life-strange-episode-2-dev-talks-us-about-whats-next-max-arcadia-bay-exclusive-424890 |title='Life is Strange Episode 2' Dev Talks To Us About What's Next For Max In Arcadia Bay [EXCLUSIVE] |first=Zulai |last=Serrano |date=23 March 2015 |work=[[IBT Media#Assets|iDigitalTimes]] |accessdate=25 March 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324104026/http://www.idigitaltimes.com/life-strange-episode-2-dev-talks-us-about-whats-next-max-arcadia-bay-exclusive-424890 |archivedate=24 March 2015  }}</ref> For the sake of serving the [[Realism (arts)|realism]], the supernatural elements were designed as a metaphor for the characters' inner conflict,<ref name=\"innerconflict\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamereactor.eu/news/288154/Life+is+Strange+-+%22Supernatural+things+merely+metaphors%22/ |title=Life is Strange \u2013 \"Supernatural things merely metaphors\" |first=Bengt |last=Lemne |date=26 January 2015 |work=[[Gamereactor]] |accessdate=26 January 2015 |archivedate= 6 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206225023/http://www.gamereactor.eu/news/288154/Life%2Bis%2BStrange%2B-%2B%22Supernatural%2Bthings%2Bmerely%2Bmetaphors%22/ |url-status=live  }}</ref> and experts were consulted to tackle the subject of [[Youth suicide|teen suicide]].<ref name=\"experts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/3/15/11226888/life-is-strange-gdc-2016 |title=How Life is Strange just might save lives \u2014 in-game and in real life |first=Allegra |last=Frank |date=15 March 2016 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=24 March 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160318134333/http://www.polygon.com/2016/3/15/11226888/life-is-strange-gdc-2016 |archivedate=18 March 2016  }}</ref> The score was composed by Jonathan Morali of the band [[Syd Matters]].<ref name=\"perspective\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2015/01/29/life-is-strange-pc-ps4-xbox-one-video/|title=Life is Strange launch trailer and final dev diary released|first=Stephany|last=Nunneley|date=29 January 2015|work=[[VG247]]|accessdate=21 July 2015|archivedate=29 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150129233119/http://www.vg247.com/2015/01/29/life-is-strange-pc-ps4-xbox-one-video/|url-status=live}}</ref> Inspired by modern [[indie folk]] music,<ref name=\"50%\" /><ref name=\"highlighting\" /> the soundtrack was intended to inform the mood of the game.<ref name=\"repercussion\" /> The music contains a blend of licensed tracks and composed pieces.<ref name=\"50%\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dualshockers.com/2014/10/09/life-is-strange-creative-director-jean-maxime-moris-talks-atmosphere-choices-and-female-leads/|title=Life Is Strange Creative Director Jean-Maxime Moris Talks Atmosphere, Choices, and Female Leads|first=Joel|last=Taveras|date=9 October 2014|work=DualShockers|accessdate=11 November 2014|archivedate=12 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112040959/http://www.dualshockers.com/2014/10/09/life-is-strange-creative-director-jean-maxime-moris-talks-atmosphere-choices-and-female-leads/|url-status=live}}</ref> Featured artists include [[Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez (singer)|Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez]], [[Mogwai]], [[Breton (band)|Breton]], [[Amanda Palmer]], [[Brian Viglione]], [[Bright Eyes (band)|Bright Eyes]], Message to Bears, [[Local Natives]], Syd Matters, [[Sparklehorse]], [[Angus & Julia Stone]], [[alt-J]], Mud Flow<ref name=\"artists\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/these-are-the-songs-in-life-is-strange/1100-6425751/ |title=These Are the Songs in Life is Strange |first=Alexa Ray |last=Corriea |date=7 March 2015 |work=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=7 March 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150309211114/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/these-are-the-songs-in-life-is-strange/1100-6425751/ |archivedate=9 March 2015  }}</ref> and [[Foals (band)|Foals]].<ref name=\"NAEU\" />\n\n==Release==\nSquare Enix and Dontnod announced ''Life Is Strange'' on 11 August 2014.<ref name=\"direct\">{{cite web|url=http://eu.square-enix.com/en/blog/announcing-life-strange|title=Announcing Life is Strange!|first=Toby|last=Palm|date=11 August 2014|work=[[Square Enix]]|accessdate=10 December 2014|archivedate=21 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021194250/http://eu.square-enix.com/en/blog/announcing-life-strange|url-status=live}}</ref> The episodes were released digitally on [[Microsoft Windows|PC]] via [[Steam (software)|Steam]], [[PlayStation 3]] and [[PlayStation 4]] via [[PlayStation Network]], and [[Xbox 360]] and [[Xbox One]] via [[Xbox Live]] between 30 January 2015 and 20 October 2015.<ref name=\"30 January 2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2014/12/17/life-is-strange-gets-a-release-date-and-pricing-info|title=Life is Strange Gets a Release Date and Pricing Info|first=Wesley|last=Copeland|date=17 December 2014|work=[[IGN]]|accessdate=17 December 2014|archivedate=17 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217003020/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/12/17/life-is-strange-gets-a-release-date-and-pricing-info|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"20 October 2015\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezone.com/news/life-is-strange-episode-5-release-date-revealed-in-new-trailer-3426071 |title=Life is Strange Episode 5 release date revealed in new trailer |first=Mike |last=Boccher |date=7 October 2015 |work=GameZone |accessdate=12 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010095519/http://www.gamezone.com/news/life-is-strange-episode-5-release-date-revealed-in-new-trailer-3426071 |archivedate=10 October 2015  }}</ref> In November 2014, the publisher said they were interested in releasing [[Video game packaging|physical copies]] of the game, but said that at that time they were \"100 per cent focused on the digital release\".<ref name=\"per cent\">{{cite web|url=http://www.videogamer.com/ps4/life_is_strange/news/square_enix_considering_boxed_release_for_life_is_strange.html|title=Square Enix considering boxed release for Life is Strange|first=David|last=Scammell|date=19 November 2014|work=VideoGamer.com|accessdate=6 December 2014|archivedate=8 December 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208080118/http://www.videogamer.com/ps4/life_is_strange/news/square_enix_considering_boxed_release_for_life_is_strange.html|url-status=live}}</ref> One year later, the retail edition was set to be released for the PC, PS4 and Xbox One in North America on 19 January 2016 and in Europe on 22 January 2016; the [[Special edition|limited edition]] had an artbook, the soundtrack, score, and a director's commentary.<ref name=\"NAEU\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/11/23/life-is-strange-limited-edition-coming-to-north-america-for-pc/178900/ |title=Life Is Strange Limited Edition Coming to North America for PC |first=Adnan |last=Riaz |date=23 November 2015 |work=Hardcore Gamer |accessdate=23 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124115414/http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/11/23/life-is-strange-limited-edition-coming-to-north-america-for-pc/178900/ |archivedate=24 November 2015  }}</ref><ref name=\"score\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/11/12/life-is-strange-limited-edition-announced/176838/ |title=Life is Strange Limited Edition Announced |first=Adam |last=Beck |date=12 November 2015 |work=Hardcore Gamer |accessdate=12 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115010710/http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/11/12/life-is-strange-limited-edition-announced/176838/ |archivedate=15 November 2015  }}</ref> A Japanese version was released for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 3 and PlayStation 4 on 3 March 2016.<ref name=\"japanese\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/12/10/life-is-stranges-japanese-version-receives-a-release-date/181870/ |title=Life Is Strange\u2019s Japanese Version Receives a Release Date |first=Adnan |last=Riaz |date=10 December 2015 |work=Hardcore Gamer |accessdate=10 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151211050238/http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/12/10/life-is-stranges-japanese-version-receives-a-release-date/181870/ |archivedate=11 December 2015  }}</ref> [[Feral Interactive]] ported ''Life Is Strange'' for [[OS X]], released on 16 June 2016,<ref name=\"mac\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/275134/Life_is_Strange_ndash_out_now_on_the_Mac_App_Store_Thecritically_acclaimed_Life_is_Strangetrade_is_now_available_on_the